O-LATTICE ROTATIONAL ACCESS SYSTEM

Dynamic Geometric Authentication & Fragmented Public Grid Model


---

1. CORE CONCEPT

The system is based on a large geometric structure called an O-lattice grid

The grid contains multiple O-shaped nodes with visible dots and spatial relationships

All users see the same public grid at any given moment

Security is not based on hidden data, but on interpretation logic



---

2. USER SECRET (PRIVATE LAYER)

Each user holds a simple private memory key:

A short numeric code (e.g. 69069)

A personal interpretation logic

A traversal rule set for reading O structures


Example of interpretation logic:

Start position (e.g. 12 o’clock / hidden north)

Direction (clockwise or counterclockwise)

Step skipping rule (e.g. every 2nd or 3rd node)

Center behavior (active, inverted, or neutral state)

Rotation or phase switching rules


This logic is:

not stored on-chain

not visible publicly

stable across time



---

3. PUBLIC GRID SYSTEM

A shared O-lattice grid is visible to all users

It consists of multiple O structures arranged in a spatial field

Each O contains:

dots (data points)

spacing (distance encoding)

rotational orientation

center node



Important property:

The same grid is shown to everyone

No user-specific visible separation exists



---

4. GRID REGISTRATION & INTERACTION

When a user interacts with the system:

The system randomly selects one or more O nodes

The user must decode them using their private logic

Only the correct interpretation produces valid authentication


After successful decoding:

That specific O becomes marked as used

Its state is stored as part of historical interaction



---

5. PROGRESSIVE O MARKING SYSTEM

After each successful use:

The selected O is permanently marked

Its state changes (consumed / altered / recorded)

Future verification involving that O is affected


This creates:

historical state dependency

evolving authentication surface

progressive reduction of usable attack surface



---

6. ATTACKER MODEL PROBLEM

An attacker faces multiple unknowns:

Which O nodes have already been used

Which O nodes are active or expired

What interpretation logic is applied

What traversal rules are used

What historical state each O carries


Additionally:

Any wrong guess results in immediate rejection

The attacker receives no reliable signal about correctness beyond failure



---

7. TIME-BASED GRID REGENERATION

The public grid is not static.

It evolves:

The grid can regenerate periodically

Time intervals are not necessarily visible

High system usage accelerates regeneration

Old grids become invalid or fragmented


Effects:

Attacker cannot study one stable system

Observation time is limited

Structure continuously shifts



---

8. HIGH-LOAD SECURITY EFFECT

Increased user activity increases grid changes

Multiple users interacting simultaneously:

force faster grid evolution

fragment attacker analysis window



Result:

The system becomes dynamically self-defending under load



---

9. INTERPRETATION-BASED IDENTITY

Identity is defined by:

The ability to correctly interpret O structures

The stability of private traversal logic

The consistency of decoding behavior over time


Not by:

stored passwords

static private keys

fixed credentials



---

10. ENTITY GROUPING & ADDRESS SYSTEM (SOS WRAPPER USE CASE)

This system can be used for:

grouping multiple blockchain addresses under one entity

creating proof-of-continuity across wallets

linking identity evolution over time


Process:

User performs proof-mint events using different addresses

Each proof uses O-lattice interpretation validation

System compares new proofs with historical SOS event structure

If consistent, addresses are grouped under same entity



---

11. ADDRESS MIGRATION & RECOVERY

If a user loses access to an old address:

They can still prove identity using interpretation logic

They generate new address

They re-attach it to existing entity group


Because:

Identity is tied to interpretation continuity, not wallet persistence



---

12. SECURITY MODEL SUMMARY

The system achieves security through:

Shared public geometry (no hidden structures)

Private interpretation logic (user-held secret)

Progressive marking of used O nodes

Time-based grid regeneration

Fragmented authentication challenges

High uncertainty for attackers

Continuous state evolution



---

13. CORE PRINCIPLE

The geometry is public and constantly changing

The interpretation is private and stable

Identity emerges from the interaction between both



---

FINAL STATEMENT

This system defines a new type of authentication model where:

Security is not stored in secrecy alone

But in evolving geometric interpretation across a shared, dynamic structure

Where each successful access reshapes the future attack surface



